, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1300–":"about 1300–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1321–Female":"1321–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1340–1392":"1340–1392","1394–Male":"1394–Deceased","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1300":"1300","1321":"1321","<1394>":"1394","Abt 1325":"about 1325","1340":"1340","1394":"1394","1392":"1392","1308":"1308","Abt 1339":"about 1339","Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, City of York Constituency, North Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","Escrick, , Yorkshire, England":"Escrick, Yorkshire, England","<Of Eastkrick, Yrkshr, Engl>":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Stourton, Stafford, England":"Stourton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lascelles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laswell","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Lascelles  . This surname is also found as   Lacefield  ."]},{"name":"Lasell","meanings":["English: variant of   Lascelles  ."]},{"name":"Lacelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Walter de Lascelles of Escrick was born about 1300, in Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph Lascelles, was -4 and his mother, Maud Constable, was -6. He married Agnes Radcliffe about 1339, in Escrick, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1300–":"umbes 1300–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1321–Female":"1321–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1340–1392":